<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="261" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,260,285]" pageId="2" pageNumber="261">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, a combination of “ 
<emphasis box="[800,858,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="261">cerv-</emphasis>
” meaning deer, and “ 
<emphasis box="[1110,1208,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="261">cornutus</emphasis>
” meaning hornlike, refers to the antler-like aedeagal apodemes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="261" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,332,357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="261">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species can be easily distinguished from other species of the genus by its long and slender aedeagal shaft and elongated bilobed aedeagal apodemes (
<figureCitation box="[804,872,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[173,1420,202,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[167,1431,193,1930]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Riseveinus cervcornutus sp. nov.: 1. male habitus, dorsal view; 2. male habitus, lateral view; 3. male head and thorax, dorsal view; 4. male face; 5. male pygofer, lateral view; 6. male pygofer side, lateral view; 7. connective and style, ventral view; 8. aedeagal, ventral view; 9. aedeagal, lateral view; 10. subgenital plate, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2607074/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="261">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
